M3: Time Series Decomposition Assignment¶

Assignment Instructions:¶

Use the data in the file ConstructionTimeSeriesDatav2.csv, which was distributed with the course files within the M3 folder.

  • This data describes private and public spending on construction in the United States from 2002 through 2013 with partial data for 2014.
  • Data source: U.S. Census Bureau (https://www.census.gov/construction/c30/historical_data.html)
  • Decompose the private and public spending data series using the most appropriate of the two time series decomposition methods that were demonstrated in the videos.

Similar to the methods used during the class lectures, a general model for the Private and Public spending on Construction data. Specifically, using this model:

$H\left(m \right) = T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right) + \epsilon \left( m \right)$

where

  • $H\left( m \right)$ = Monthly Spend (in Millions of Dollars) $m$
  • $m$ = the index of the month
  • $T\left( m \right)$ = $T$ represents the trend of the data which, in this case, could be nonlinear. $T\left( m \right)$ is the trend value for Month $m$.
  • $C\left( m \right)$ = Cyclicality demand component which plays an analogous role to seasonality, $S\left( q \right)$, except that the pattern repeats after period whose duration might not be one year.
  • $\epsilon \left( m \right)$ is the portion of demand that we will not be able to fit with $T \left(m \right)$ and $C \left( m \right)$.

The appropriate window size for the two respective data sets are 28 and 31 for the Private Construction Values and Public Construction Values, respectively.

Below will be the calculation of the average squared error for both the private and public contructions values for the window sizes mentioned above.

df['MovAvg'] = np.NaN
df['sqErr'] = np.NaN

# Create a seperate DF for both the public and private construction values, as they will have different window sizes
dfPri = df.drop(['Total Construction','Public Construction'], axis=1)
dfPub = df.drop(['Total Construction','Private Construction'], axis=1)

winPri = 28
winPub = 31

winPri = winPri - winPri % 2
winPub = winPub - winPub % 2

# Compute the moving average in the loop below using a window centered on the data point whose average is being computed
# Private 
for i in range(int(winPri/2),dfPri.shape[0]-int(winPri/2)):
    dfPri.loc[dfPri.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*dfPri.iloc[i - int(winPri/2)]['Private Construction'] + dfPri.iloc[i - int(winPri/2)+1:i + int(winPri/2)]['Private Construction'].sum() + 0.5*dfPri.iloc[i + int(winPri/2)]['Private Construction'])/float(winPri)
dfPri['sqErr'] = (dfPri['Private Construction'] - dfPri['MovAvg'])**2

# Public
for i in range(int(winPub/2),dfPub.shape[0]-int(winPub/2)):
    dfPub.loc[dfPub.index[i],'MovAvg'] = (0.5*dfPub.iloc[i - int(winPub/2)]['Public Construction'] + dfPub.iloc[i - int(winPub/2)+1:i + int(winPub/2)]['Public Construction'].sum() + 0.5*dfPub.iloc[i + int(winPub/2)]['Public Construction'])/float(winPub)
dfPub['sqErr'] = (dfPub['Public Construction'] - dfPub['MovAvg'])**2

# The moving average cannot be applied to all rows and we need to delete those rows because we cannot use them in the analysis
dfPri.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)
dfPub.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)

dfPri['R1'] = dfPri['Private Construction'] - dfPri['MovAvg']

# Private Construction First
maxCorr = 0.0
period = np.NaN
print('Private Construction Auto Correlation Analysis')
print('')
for i in range(1,37):
    corr = dfPri['R1'].autocorr(lag=i)
    print('Correlation, lag ',i,'   ',corr)
    if corr > maxCorr:
        maxCorr = corr
        period = i
print('period = ',period,'     Maximum Correlation = ',maxCorr)

print('')

The code cell below executes the following:

  • Computes the remaining residual home sales to be explained, $R2$, after subtracting the cyclical component, $C \left( m \right)$: this is the $\epsilon \left( m \right)$ in our model.
  • Computes the error, $R2$, as a percentage of the demand time series.
  • Computes the mathematical model 'fit', composed of the trend and cyclical components: $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$.
  • Plots the fit of the model $T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right)$ with the original data, $H \left( m \right)$.
  • Computes the average absolute error of $R2Error$ of the original demand time series.
  • Retains the sqErr column because shows the trend data relative to the original data series for each month, and calculates the cumulative square error as well.

Appendix - Script to Determine the "Optimial" Window Sizes¶

In [ ]:
df1 = dfAppendix

df1['Pri_MovAvg'] = np.NaN
df1['Pri_sqErr'] = np.NaN
# Can't add the public at the same time, or it results in an error with the calculation of the window size.
df1['Pub_MovAvg'] = np.NaN 
df1['Pub_sqErr'] = np.NaN

#df1.index = pd.to_datetime(df['Month-Year'], format='%b-%y')
#df1.index = pd.DatetimeIndex(freq='M', start=pd.Timestamp(year=2002, month=1, day=1), periods = len(df1['Private Construction']))

#print(len(data),'\n',data)

# Determine the Appropriate window size for Public and Private Construction
winPriPub = pd.DataFrame(data = list(range(20,50)), columns = ['windowSize'])
winPriPub['PriAvgSqErr']=np.NaN
winPriPub['PubAvgSqErr']=np.NaN
for win in range(len(winPriPub)):
    window = winPriPub['windowSize'][win]
    window = window - window % 2
    dfLoop = df1
    dfLoop2 = df1
    # Compute the moving average in the loop below using a window centered on the data point whose average is being computed
    for i in range(int(window/2),dfLoop.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
        dfLoop.loc[dfLoop.index[i],'Pri_MovAvg'] = (0.5*dfLoop.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Private Construction'] + dfLoop.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'].sum() + 0.5*dfLoop.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Private Construction'])/float(window)
    for i in range(int(window/2),dfLoop2.shape[0]-int(window/2)):
        dfLoop2.loc[dfLoop2.index[i],'Pub_MovAvg'] = (0.5*dfLoop2.iloc[i - int(window/2)]['Public Construction'] + dfLoop2.iloc[i - int(window/2)+1:i + int(window/2)]['Public Construction'].sum() + 0.5*dfLoop2.iloc[i + int(window/2)]['Public Construction'])/float(window)
    dfLoop['Pri_sqErr'] = (dfLoop['Private Construction'] - dfLoop['Pri_MovAvg'])**2
    dfLoop2['Pub_sqErr'] = (dfLoop2['Public Construction'] - dfLoop2['Pub_MovAvg'])**2
    # The moving average cannot be applied to all rows and we need to delete those rows because we cannot use them in the analysis
    dfLoop.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)
    dfLoop2.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)
    winPriPub['PriAvgSqErr'][win]=sum(dfLoop['Pri_sqErr'])/len(dfLoop)
    winPriPub['PubAvgSqErr'][win]=sum(dfLoop2['Pub_sqErr'])/len(dfLoop2)

print(winPriPub)
